  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] ▣ : '
    value: 爰
english:
  title: Memorial Offering to Master Chunggyeong
  author: Seok Bok-am
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I contemplate the spirit of the departed: gentle and warm in nature, clear and even in conduct, with movements arising from heaven itself—utterly free from artifice. In conversation, composure flows naturally, embodying the ordinary and the straightforward. Early did he cast off the dusty realm, soaring beyond the boundaries of things. His knowledge encompassed the three teachings, his spirit surpassed all quarters. Long he dwelt at the gate of true awakening, deep he entered the chambers of perfect fusion. When guiding those who came seeking, he persevered through daylong instruction without weariness. When investigating the ultimate principle, he labored through the years without satiation. Four forms of life leaned upon him as upon a bridge across the stream. The seven celestial spheres gazed upon him as upon the stars themselves.

    Though I, in my humble unworthiness, have always held reverent longing for him, when duty called to the Capital of Flowers to seek his editorial hand, and later to trace the transmission of the lamp on Pine Mountain, walking always at his heels—whether in his retreat at Turtle Peak or in his final dwelling at Dragon's Rest, step by step I followed his begging bowl and staff. Yet my shallow roots and thin capacity could never grasp the marrow, though his boundless compassion endlessly poured forth his heart. Looking back upon twenty-four years of his benevolence, I see them as blessings of ten thousand eons of karmic affinity.

    Now that he has departed, where shall I turn for refuge? To shed winter robes and cast off summer garments—this is the natural play of existence; to ascend to heaven and enter Buddha-lands—this too is the wandering ordained by our very nature. Yet he stood as teacher to ten thousand kings, lived through eighty springs. His name flows through all lands; his way illuminates heaven and earth. As his transformative influence reached its fullness, he yielded to worldly law and entered perfect extinction. His light shines both before and after; surely he harbors no regret from beginning to end.

    Yet I cannot bear this long separation—how can I hope to meet again? The great beam has snapped; who now supports the ancestral hall? The mighty oar has sunk; how shall I cross the sea of suffering? I cannot restrain these tears—they fall not for myself alone. I recall that before, caught up in dharma work, I could not be at his side; hearing suddenly of his illness, I rushed home in haste, yet could not receive his final teachings in proper stillness. Yet the karma between us has been deepest; my sorrow only deepens.

    On this morning of the seventh vigil, I spread this humble altar of return to the three paths. With meager offerings and a humble heart I pour forth my grief. Deign to know my sincerity and to accept this offering.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three teachings' (三敎) likely refers to Buddhism, Daoism, and Confucianism, suggesting the master's broad spiritual learning.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'seven celestial spheres' (七象) and reference to 'four forms of life' are Buddhist cosmological concepts referring to different levels of sentient existence.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Capital of Flowers' (花都) refers to the royal capital, likely Seoul.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Turtle Peak'' and ''Dragon''s Rest'' are names of Buddhist temples or meditation sites where the master dwelt.'
  - key: ''
    value: The 'seventh vigil' refers to the seventh day after death, an important observance in Buddhist funeral rites.
